I decided to eat at this restaurant by looking at google reviews. As a Turkish person, I was so excited to learn that they might be really good Turkish restaurant nearby my hotel. We ordered Lahmacun, Cag kebap and iskender. Honestly, the Lahmacun I had at this restaurant is probably worst Lahmacun I have ever had in my life. Real Lahmacun dough is supposed to be very thin but Lahmacuns at this restaurant are so thick almost just like pizza. Bottom of the Lahmacun was little bit burned but top of the Lahmacun was not cooked. The top part was still like uncooked dough. Also, real Lahmacun has good amount of ground beef. When I was eating the Lahmacun, I felt like eating vegan Lahmacun. They probably put very little ground beef and put too much vegetables. And the vegetables had no flavor neither. It didn’t have any spicy flavor at all. “The chef “ of the Lahmacun should look up how to make Lahmacun on internet. They can learn it on the internet. The second food we ate was Iskender kebap. Which was not good either. Iskender kebap is made with PIDE bread , gyro meat, source and butter and yogurt. They were too lazy to make pide bread for the Iskender kebap. They literally used loaf of bread that you can not use for Iskender. Their Iskender meat was not bad. But the source they put on top was bland . And another failure of Iskender was the yogurt they served with it. Yogurt is supposed to be thicker just like Greek yogurt. But the yogurt they used was not good at all. It was bad. The third food was Cag kebap. Cag kebap meat was actually good. It could be better but after Lahmacun and Iskender taste, I would say Cag kebap was good. However the bad part was the rice and yogurt sauce. The rice was too much and had no flavor. I littered only ate the chickpeas. Yogurt sauce was really bad. They should add some good hot sauce. Overall I think my experience was bad. After I paid the bill, I left. When I got to the my car, the waitress come and asked me why I didn’t leave tip and gave me the bill back and made me to leave her some tip. In total, I paid $70 for 2 Lahmacun, 1 Iskender and 1 Cag kebap. Probably Worst restaurant experience in my life.

After twenty-seven years living in Wicker Park, we've seen this store front through its various incarnations, from video store to a couple of mediocre restaurants, but they've hit the jackpot with Cafe Istanbul. From the moment we walked in we knew we were in for something special. The renovations have taken it from a cold open room to a warm, inviting place to relax and enjoy some truly spectacular Turkish food. We were greeted warmly at the front desk, and even though we didn't have a reservation we were seated promptly. We started with some delicious and complimentary hearth-baked bread served with a yogurt-garlic-carrot dip that was to-die-for. For an appetizer we split the SU BOREGI, homemade dough filled with feta cheese and fresh dill, served with fresh dill and creamy yogurt garlic sauce. This was reminiscent (to me anyway) of a Turkish-style kugel. Very hearty and satisfying. For our entrees we went with BRAISED SHORT-RIB, red wine and fresh herbs, served with soft polenta and ISLIM SARMASI, Braised lamb shoulder, wrapped in eggplant, served with basmati rice pilaf. OMG so good and so tender! And the portions are enormous. We had to take half of our food home to enjoy another day. Note that the short rib takes about twenty minutes to prepare, but it is definitely worth the wait. Prices are reasonable and the staff were friendly and welcoming. We highly recommend Cafe Istanbul and can't wait to return.

This place was happening with hustle by the staff and all tables full! Delicious feta salad with unusual shredded feta over the top, along with beets and olives. My doner entree was a little on the fatty side, but my husband's lamb wrapped in eggplant was delicious. The baklava dessert was made with plenty of honey and came in a generous portion. In fact, all the dishes were very generous! The bread at the outset was delicious, served with complementary roasted eggplant/pepper spread. The gorgeous copper hood in the kitchen is a treat to behold!

Amazing. The food is great! The service was that perfect mix of attentiveness without seeming overbearing. I really appreciate when your server notes a distinct flavor profile of something that people may not prefer (ie: I would have not enjoyed my drink if our server had not pointed out that what I was going to order had a strong licorice taste). It is a small space, that didn't feel too crowded as much as cozy.  The food was seasoned very well and eveything was so fresh. I could be happy eating just the rice- it was so good. I ordered the lamb shoulder kebab and it was excellent. We also had the zucchini 'pancakes' which were more like fritters and they were delicious.  I'm pretty sure you could order anything and it would not disappoint.  We were too full to order dessert but it is nice that you can see food on tables near your and the desserts looked intriguing. They serve a muffulletta style bread with eggplant that just begins your meal on a high note and it continues from there. It always warms my heart when people understand how to properly season food. They also have a good amount of vegetarian options- too. And there is even a parking lot! Definitely going back and I can't wait to- either.

Turkish cousine is definitely of the best kitchens in the world and this place is the best one in chicago in serving delicious turkish food with a good presentation. I feel lucky to have Istanbul Cafe and its experienced chef in Chicago, they offer very fine tastes of Turkey and mediterranean cuisine to Chicagoans. Tonight we had grilled liver and döner, and everything tasted great, thank you chef.

Simply outstanding presentation of primarily genuine Turkish cuisine.  Not over extensive options but just the right variety of mainly popular dishes.  A good mix of kebabs as well as traditional "home cooking" with today's touch, not to mention fine selection of mezes (tapas).  All exquisitely prepped, deliciously tasty,  well presented, moderately priced, very easy parking, knowledged & attentive servers, not to mention that this is a quite nicely furnished locale with white table cloths and comfy seating.  Plus, very good selection of surprisingly satisfactory Turkish wines.  There is also an adjoining nice cozy, relatively well stacked bar within the restaurant facing that amazing open wood fire pit where you can eye witness the horizontally stacked marinated rotating lamb/beef "cag" kebab dripping and lightly spreading out-of-this-world aroma!  An open invitation and challenge of; Try Me!  Simply put, that alone by itself is the epitome of carnivorous dish that must be experienced by all meat lovers. Two words; outrageously delicious.  By the way, there are also numerous tasty dishes to satisfy vegetarians as well.  In essence, it was such a pleasant surprise to finally experience a really enjoyable, well layed out, attractively furnished Turkish restaurant in Chicago.  Ohh, don't omit the omni present Turkish coffee with kunefe desert to top it all off and whether you ask for it or not, they will serve you a cup of Turkish tea on the house!  Bon appetit.

Ok this place is seriously incredible. Piping hot Turkish bread with dollops of sesame seeds arrive at the table unannounced with delicious eggplant or carrot spreads. We naturally added more delicious spreads to accompany the perfect bread (the patlican salartisi is LEGIT one of the tastiest morsels of food I have put in my mouth in life), along with a transcendent lamb skewed dish which combines the char of shawarma with the heft of a filet. Then they surprised us with decadent Turkish flan (see pic) that we tried to eat a polite amount of, not because it wasn’t super tasty, but because we had already gorged on everything in our plate. Cafe Istanbul is down right amazing. I don’t do reviews. Ever. But I’m making an exception for this place. Turkish chefs. Wood burning stove.  Parking. Fresh/flavorful food. Great service. Little flavor explosions with every bite. Oh happy day.  I intend on coming here on a weekly basis.

Fantastic experience!! My wife and I went for lunch a week after it opened and ordered the soup, an appetizer, seafood salad, and the donor wrap. Every course was flavorful, well-sized, and authentically Turkish. The wait staff was extremely helpful and told us about their wood burning stove and their chefs from Turkey. The care they take in crafting the menu is abundantly clear- I wouldn’t make modifications to these dishes. We’ll be coming back to this spot often for lunch or dinner.
